'''John Luigi Mica''' (born January 27, 1943) is an American businessman, consultant and [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] politician who has represented {{ushr|Florida|7|}} in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] since 1993. He was defeated by Democrat [[Stephanie Murphy]] in the November 8, 2016 general election while serving his 12th term in office.\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nMica was born in [[Binghamton, New York]] and grew up in Florida. He was educated at [[Miami Edison High School]], [[Miami-Dade Community College]] and the [[University of Florida]], where he received a degree in education and was a member of [[Delta Chi]] Fraternity and [[Florida Blue Key]]. He has been a businessman serving in the real estate, telecommunications, government affairs and consulting fields.\n\n== Early political career ==\nMica was a member of the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from 1976\u201380 and served on several committees, including the Appropriations Committee. He was a staff member for Senator [[Paula Hawkins|Paula F. Hawkins]] from 1981\u201385 and became her chief of staff.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1992\nIn 1992, Mica ran for Congress in the 7th District, previously the 4th District represented by two-term Republican [[Craig T. James]].\n\n[[File:John L. Mica.jpg|150px|left|thumb|John Mica while a member of the Florida state legislature]]\nMica won the Republican primary with 53% of the vote, defeating State Representative [[Richard Graham (politician)|Richard Graham]] (34%) and Vaughn Forrest (13%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=368334 |title=FL District 07 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Sep 01, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Democrat Dan Webster 56%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27629 |title=FL District 07 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\n;1994\u20132004\nDuring this time period, he won re-election every two years with at least 60% of the vote.<ref name=\"ourcampaigns1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1026 |title=Candidate \u2013 John L. Mica |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2006#District 7}}\nMica defeated Jack Chagnon 63%\u201337%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206805 |title=FL \u2013 District 07 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2008#District 7}}\nMica defeated [[Faye Armitage]] 62%\u201338%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=334533 |title=FL \u2013 District 07 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2010#District 7}}\nMica defeated Heather Beaven 69%\u201331%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488448 |title=FL \u2013 District 07 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2012#District 7}}\nAfter the 2010 Census, the bulk of Mica's territory became the 6th District.  However, most of the Orange County portion, including Mica's home in Winter Park, was drawn into the new 7th District.   That district had previously been the 24th District, represented by freshman Republican [[Sandy Adams]].  Mica defeated Adams in the Republican primary with 61 percent of the vote.  In the general election, Mica defeated Jason Kendall 59%\u201341%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=736117</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2014#District 7}}\nMica defeated Wes Neuman 64%\u201332%.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = November 4, 2014 General Election Official Results| work = | publisher = Florida Department of State Division of Elections| date = | url = http://election.dos.state.fl.us/elections/resultsarchive/Index.asp?ElectionDate=11/4/2014&DATAMODE=| format = | doi = | accessdate = 13 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2016#District 7}}\nIn the general election, Mica lost to Democrat [[Stephanie Murphy]] by a margin of 51%\u201349%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=801550</ref>\n\n==Policy positions==\n\n===Abortion===\nMica opposes abortion. Regarding taxpayer funding of abortion through [[Planned Parenthood]], he has said \u201cI think the majority of Americans would oppose public, federal dollars going into abortion.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martinez|first1=Jack|title=Facing Congress, Planned Parenthood CEO Defends Abortion as a Health Service|url=http://www.newsweek.com/planned-parenthood-ceo-testifies-hearing-abortion-378112|accessdate=26 September 2016|publisher=Newsweek|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\nMica voted against the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|2009 stimulus]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Finley |first1=Ben |title=Florida Primary Flier Frames Republican|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2012/07/florida-primary-flier-frames-republican/|accessdate=26 September 2016|publisher=FactCheck.org|date=July 20, 2012}}</ref> He has brought federal money for Florida highways, [[SunRail]], the Veterans Administration Medical Center, and the [[University of Central Florida]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|title=John Mica gets tune-up election out of the way, set for Democratic challenge in CD 7|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/220744-john-mica-gets-tune-election-way-set-democratic-challenge-cd-7|accessdate=26 September 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=August 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\nMica supports [[Amtrak]] [[privatization]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Larry | last = Hannan | title = John Mica, Corrine Brown split over privatizing Amtrak in Northeast | date = June 16, 2011 | url = http://jacksonville.com/news/florida/2011-06-16/story/john-mica-corrine-brown-split-over-privatizing-amtrak-northeast#ixzz29JHED1zX | work = [[The Florida Times-Union]] | accessdate = October 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2009, he earmarked $13 million for the [[Central Florida Commuter Rail]], which was supported by a client of Mica's daughter.<ref>{{cite news | first = Kenric | last = Ward | title = Report: Two Florida Congressmen Kept Earmarks in the Family | date = March 28, 2012 | url = http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/report-two-florida-congressmen-kept-earmarks-family | work = Sunshine State News | accessdate = November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMica has been opposed to the federal government contributing any additional funds towards repairing the Washington DC [[WMATA|Metrorail system]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Benjamin | last = Freed | title = Metro Chairman Tells Congress to Chip in $300 Million Per Year. Congress Yells at Metro. | date = April 13, 2016 | url = http://www.washingtonian.com/2016/04/13/metro-chairman-tells-congress-chip-300-million-per-year | work = Washingtonian Magazine | accessdate = April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Marijuana===\nAs chairman of the House Oversight Committee's subcommittee on government operations, Mica convened a hearing on marijuana legalization in 1999. It was the first such hearing since 1988. Mica opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Itkowitz|first1=Colby|title=Rep. Mica holds (another) hearing on being stoned|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/wp/2014/07/28/oversight-panel-holds-another-hearing-on-being-stoned/|website=www.washingtonpost.com|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fang|first1=Marina|title=Congressional Republicans Rail Against Legalization Of Marijuana|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/31/colorado-marijuana-legalization_n_5638758.html|accessdate=26 September 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|date=July 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Committee assignments==\nMica was chairman of the [[House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee]] from January 3, 2011 to December 2012.\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]''' (former Chairman)\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight and Government Reform Subcommittee on Information Policy, Census, and National Archives|Subcommittee on Information Policy, Census, and National Archives]]\n** [[United States House Oversight and Government Reform Subcommittee on National Security and Foreign Affairs|Subcommittee on National Security and Foreign Affairs]]\n\n==Personal life==\nMica is married to Patricia, a schoolteacher, and has two grown children. He lives in Winter Park, Florida. He is the brother of former Representative [[Daniel A. Mica]], while his other brother, David, is a former ranking staffer of Senator [[Lawton Chiles]]. He is a member of the Kennedy Center Board of Trustees and the Coast Guard Academy Board of Visitors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Company Overview of The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/Research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=231716548&privcapId=4279962&previousCapId=145449191&previousTitle=Infofree.com|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Congressional Record|date=July 2007|publisher=Government Printing Office|edition=V. 153, Pt. 15|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nMica and his wife own six properties on [[Capitol Hill]]. From 2006\u201313, they paid $1,071.81 in 17 penalty payments for paying their property taxes late.<ref>{{cite news |first=Will |last=Sommer |title=District-Bashing Congressman Doesn't Pay His Own D.C. Taxes On Time |date=April 18, 2016 |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/looselips/2016/04/18/district-bashing-congressman-doesnt-pay-his-own-d-c-taxes-on-time/#more-29348 |work=Washington City Paper |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.house.gov/mica/ Congressman John L. Mica] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.micaforcongress.com/ John Mica for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/John_Mica_%5BR-07%5D|John Mica}}\n* {{C-SPAN|johnmica}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = m000689 | ballot = John_L._Mica | nndb = 049/000039929 | votesmart = 26805 | govtrack = 400273 | opencong = 400273 | rollcall = 108 | politifact = john-mica | fec = H2FL08055 | opensecrets = N00002793 | assets = john-mica | legistorm = 375/Rep_John_Mica.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = FL/John_Mica.htm | congress = john-mica/800 | worldcat = np-mica,%20john%20l | cspan = 26395 | rose = | imdb = 1929747 | bloomberg = john-mica | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = gIQAGSEKAP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sam Gibbons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Florida's 2nd congressional district]]|years=1993\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephanie Murphy]]<br>{{small|Elect}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Oberstar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|House Transportation Committee]]|years=2011\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill Shuster]]}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carolyn Maloney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=47th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucille Roybal-Allard]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FL-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{US House Transportation and Infrastructure chairs}}\n{{U.S. Florida Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mica, John}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Florida House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Binghamton, New York]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:University of Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]"}]}}}}